Paige:

I applaud your efforts at providing a larger body of Quickscript 
material.Your email did not ask for a critique - but I just love 
doing them.  It&#39;s not that I know that much, but I learn a lot more 
looking at another person&#39;s work than my own.

As you will see, I am not about to get into the &quot;correct&quot; 
pronunciation quagmire, except in one instance, where I found it not 
correct, or incorrect, but an interesting option.  I hope this 
doesn&#39;t crash your fancy system . Here goes:



Witches&#39; scene from Shakespeare&#39;s Macbeth - written out in full with 
no abbreviations or half-letters.  I do use the seven standard 
abbreviations which Read suggested even writers of junior Quikscript 
should use.

1 wic.  `eG SAl wI TrI mIt agiG?
Since this is a poem, and most lines rhyme, I could see the 
possibility of spelling this agEn, to get the same vowel sound as 
rEG. It&#39;s an advantage of the Shavian system that author&#39;s could 
dictate exactly how they want their words pronounced. (I bet in 
Shakespeare&#39;s day the two words did rhyme without forcing.)
	iG TandD, lFtGIN, P iG rEG?
Taking the word rFtiN from Pg 24 of the Quickscript manual as a 
guide, &quot;lightning&quot; should read lFtGiN

2 wic.  `eG H hDlIbDlIz dan,
	`eG H bAtulz lYst And wan.
Androcles uses in Shavian script lost instead of lYst.  lYst suggests 
a really broad vowel sound as in &quot;law&quot; lY. Southerners here in 
America would say  lYst, but most of the rest of the country would be 
more inclined to  lost. But this is the kind of nit-picking I vowed 
not get into.

3 wic.  HAt wil b X H set v san.
1 wic.  `X H plEs?
2 wic.  apoG H hIT.
3 wic.  HX tM mIt wiT /mAkbeT.
1 wic.  F kam, /grEmYlkin.
2 wic.  pAdak kYlz.
3 wic.  anoG !
Yl.  fX z fQl, And fQl z fX:
	havD TrM H [an oddity here:my text adds &lt;fog n&gt;] filTI X.

/mAkbeT   Akt wan, sIn wan
The same scene using the standard abbreviations and half-letters:
If the first word is really &quot;the&quot;, and you choose not to use the 
abbreviation H then is&#39;nt He more correct? If the second word is 
supposed to be &quot;same&quot;, I would say sEm . If the third word is 
&quot;scene&quot;, then it should be written as it was the line  above &lt;sIn&gt;. 
&quot;Using&quot; (like &quot;musing&quot;) would be &lt;Msing&gt; No need to repeat the sound 
b twice in abbreviations and I hear a z at the end not an s.

1 wic.  `eG Sl w TrI mIt agiG?
	iG TandD, lFtGIN, P iG rEG?
Again on page 24, the Senior script version of &quot;writing&quot; is rFtN , so 
lightning would be lFtGN.
2 wic.  `eG H hDlIbDlIz dan,
	`eG H bAtulz lYst n @an.
3 wic.  Ht l b X H set v san.
1 wic.  `X H plEs?
2 wic.  apoG H hIT.
3 wic.  HX t mIt wi /mAkbeT.
1 wic.  F km, /grEmYlkin.
2 wic.  pAdak kYlz.
3 wic.  anoG !
Yl.  fX z fQl, n fQl z fX:
	havD TrM H filTI X.

Now how about the other Five Acts....?


